{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611358"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:10:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:10:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16210"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16210"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.41,0.27,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8901"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115380"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8901"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16210"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97383"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8403"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21180"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21183"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115380"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe breast contains specialised stromal tissues that provide structural and functional support to the glandular elements. Different types of stroma are found in distinct regions of the breast tissue.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the cellular composition of intralobular stroma in the breast?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dense collagen fibres with scattered fibroblasts","Adipocytes and myoepithelial cells with capillaries","Fibroblasts, lymphocytes, plasma cells and macrophages","Elastic fibres with resident dendritic cells","Reticular fibres with scattered mast cells"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efibroblasts, lymphocytes, plasma cells and macrophages\u003C/strong\u003E are the key cellular components of intralobular stroma. This specialised loose connective tissue surrounds the epithelial structures within terminal duct lobular units (TDLUs) and provides both structural and immunological support.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDense collagen fibres with scattered fibroblasts\u003C/strong\u003E better describes interlobular stroma, which surrounds larger ducts. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdipocytes and myoepithelial cells with capillaries\u003C/strong\u003E are present in breast tissue but are not characteristic of intralobular stroma. \u003Cstrong\u003EElastic fibres with resident dendritic cells\u003C/strong\u003E are more prominent around larger ducts rather than in intralobular stroma, while \u003Cstrong\u003Ereticular fibres with scattered mast cells\u003C/strong\u003E may be present but do not represent the predominant cellular composition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cellular composition of intralobular stroma is important for normal breast development, hormone responsiveness, and immune surveillance. Blood vessels are also present throughout the intralobular stroma to support these functions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The intralobular stroma is the specialised connective tissue within terminal duct lobular units (TDLUs) that contains cellular components essential for breast function.","The intralobular stroma is distinct from interlobular stroma, which is more collagenous and surrounds larger ducts.","The cellular composition of intralobular stroma is important for breast development, function and immune surveillance."],"references":["Wiseman BS, Werb Z. Stromal effects on mammary gland development and breast cancer. Science. 2002 May 10;296(5570):1046-9. doi: 10.1126/science.1067431. PMID: 12004111; PMCID: PMC2788989","Shekhar MP, Werdell J, Santner SJ, Pauley RJ, Tait L. Breast stroma plays a dominant regulatory role in breast epithelial growth and differentiation: implications for tumor development and progression. Cancer Res. 2001 Feb 15;61(4):1320-6. PMID: 11245428","Arendt LM, Rudnick JA, Keller PJ, Kuperwasser C. Stroma in breast development and disease. Semin Cell Dev Biol. 2010 Feb;21(1):11-8. doi: 10.1016/j.semcdb.2009.10.003. Epub 2009 Oct 24. PMID: 19857593; PMCID: PMC2823823","Javed A, Lteif A. Development of the human breast. Semin Plast Surg. 2013 Feb;27(1):5-12. doi: 10.1055/s-0033-1343989. PMID: 24872732; PMCID: PMC3706056","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97383"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16210"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97383"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T14:17:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T14:17:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8901"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115380"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"}